Addressing Harassment in the Second Degree (PL 240.26(1)), the Court wrote that “a person is guilty of [this charge] when, with intent to harass, annoy, threaten or alarm another person: (1) he or she strikes, shoves, kicks, or otherwise subjects another person to physical contact, or attempts or threatens to do the same.” In this case, the Court reasoned that since defendant’s racial slurs were coupled with him spitting upon the victim (which, as noted above constitutes “physical contact”), the charge must be upheld and put before a fact finder. Therefore, the Court denied defendant’s motion as to this allegation.

Finally, the Court directed its attention to Menacing in the Third Degree (PL 120.15). A defendant is guilty of violating this statute when, “by physical menace, he or she intentionally places or attempts to place another person in fear of death, imminent serious physical injury or physical injury.” A key element in this scenario is “physical menace.” To better understand what Menacing in the Third Degree is, the Court wrote that menacing occurs when “a person who, with intent to frighten another, points a gun at him which is in fact unloaded though not known by the victim to be so” Donnino, Practice Commentary, McKinney’s Cons. Laws of N.Y., Book 39, Penal Law §120.15, at 203.

I've been pondering on this one for a few weeks - wondering how I'd frame it and put pen to paper so to speak. This may benefit some, may annoy others, and may just be confirmatory to many. Sure I may lose some followers and that's ok. Regardless, I feel it's something I must do. 

For those who read all the way through, I really appreciate your time in doing so.

Do you believe in God - do you believe that He exists?
Do you believe in Science?
Do you believe that Science can explain everything, and that if it can't be explained by science that it is not scientific?
Would you agree that any given supposition or proposition to abide by the Scientific method or criteria it must be: testable, observable, repeatable, measurable and falsifiable.

As a quick reference here is a breakdown of those five criteria.
1. testable - can what I'm proposing be tested or tried. Is it even possible to do this?
2. observable - can it be noticed, perceived, discerned and actually observed?
3. repeatable - can it be done more than once. Can the experiment or observation be repeated?
4. measurable - it must be possible to provide data or information, which can be analysed both of itself, and against other data - does it meet this requirement?
5. falsifiable - can it be proven to be false. Is it actually possible to go about proving it to be a false claim or theory?

Based on the premise of the belief in the absoluteness of Science and based on the scientific method, is it even possible to definitively hold to THE NON EXISTENCE of something, i.e God.

Would you agree, based on the above, that the non-existence of God can not be adequately explained scientifically but is rather, a position of faith?
As a statement of faith, is it equally as reasonable to believe there is a God, as it is to believe there is no God?

Could it be fair to say that it is more plausible and rational to believe in the existence of something, and indeed requires less faith, than believing in the non-existence of something.

For example we can take it as a given that art requires an artist, design requires a designer, and content requires intent.

To expand on that slightly - if we have resultant specified complexity, can we reasonably assert that such specificity and complexity would require a deliberate and intelligent first cause, or a conscious intent?

Considering the Darwinian Theory of Evolution, which is often posited as unquestioned Science, how well does it stack up against the scientific method discussed above?

Darwin's theory of evolution, juxtaposed against the Biblical narrative of God as a creator, cannot both be true. It would be remiss of me if I did not state that there is a fundamental difference between adaptation and variation, which does meet all the scientific criteria - also called micro-evolution, versus speciation - also called macro-evolution. The latter is based on assumptions and assertions.

This leads us to Aristotle's Principle of Noncontradiction, which states:
No system will operate if it is self-contradictory. No system will operate if it is inherently inconsistent, that is - it is self refuting.

Other ways to state this principle:
1. A being cannot be and not be at the same time.
2. A thing either is or is not.
3. Whatever is, is.
4. A being is what it is - and is not what it is not.

Using this principle we can pause to consider if this world and all that is in it, particularly complex lifeforms, required a massively intelligent first cause or came about by unguided and random processes over billions of years. Both cannot be true. One is true and one is false.

An indepth and honest scientific endeavour shows that highly complex systems simply do not come about naturally with no external influence. Furthermore, complex entities such as the eye, are so vastly and intrinsically structured, possessing around 15 symbiotic and sequentially dependent chemical processes, that if even one element of the chain ceases to operate as required, sight as a function ceases to work, in its entirety. Many complex entities, sight being just one, are irreducibly complex.

Considering the above, and that Darwin's theory of Evolution alludes to the non-existence of God, an assertion in non-conformance with the scientific method, it does seem reasonable to provide a counter assertion that circumstantial evidence of all we see around us, required something other than random unguided processes.

If we can rationally assume the existence of God, that He is the divine and absolute first cause of the Universe, the Earth, and all that exists within it, including humanity. Does it seem reasonable then that the Bible message is authored by Him?
Yes, this is about faith, although not blind faith. Many committed historians and researchers have concluded that the Bible, and the existence of Jesus are not merely a figment of wild imagination, but have concluded source texts to be reliable and trustworthy. Sure there are differences of opinion on some details, but that will always be the case about anything.

The salient point of this subject, is the place we are at personally. Most of humanity has at various stages experienced a prompting within our hearts and minds - a deep rooted concern about death and the hereafter.

I'm sure there are many like me, who've felt a prompting and heard that inaudible voice many times in our hearts and minds.

There is a difference between knowing God, rather than just knowing about Him.

The next section will cover the absolute basics of the Christian message.

God's Love for us
-----
John 3:16 For God so loved the world that He gave His only begotten Son, that whoever believes in Him should not perish but have everlasting life.
John 3:17 For God did not send His Son into the world to condemn the world, but that the world through Him might be saved.
John 3:18 He who believes in Him is not condemned; but he who does not believe is condemned already, because he has not believed in the name of the only begotten Son of God.
Romans 3:23 … for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God,
Isaiah 59:2 But your iniquities have separated you from your God; And your sins have hidden His face from you, So that He will not hear.

Jesus has saved us by paying the price on our behalf, for sins committed by us.
-----
Romans 10:9-10 ..that if you confess with your mouth the Lord Jesus and believe in your heart that God has raised Him from the dead, you will be saved. For with the heart one believes unto righteousness, and with the mouth confession is made unto salvation.
Revelation 3:20 Behold, I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears My voice and opens the door, I will come in to him and dine with him, and he with Me.

Why believe in God and Jesus, and be “saved”?
------
John 14:1-6
1. Let not your heart be troubled; you believe in God, believe also in Me.
2. In My Father’s house are many mansions; if it were not so, I would have told you. I go to prepare a place for you.
3. And if I go and prepare a place for you, I will come again and receive you to Myself; that where I am, there you may be also.
4. And where I go you know, and the way you know.
5. Thomas said to Him, “Lord, we do not know where You are going, and how can we know the way?”
6. Jesus said to him, “I am the way, the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through Me.

What do we have to do?
-----
Acts 2:21 And it shall come to pass, that whosoever shall call on the name of the Lord shall be saved.
1 John 1:9 If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins, and to cleanse us from all unrighteousness.

Summary
-----
The message of salvation is simple.
Sin separates us from God, but God’s plan to redeem us back to himself was by sending His son Jesus to the earth, by virgin birth, to be crucified on the cross and by doing so, pay the price for our sins.

We don't have to “work towards” salvation, we just need to accept that Jesus paid the ultimate price to save us from condemnation. Just as 1 John 1:9 says above: We confess our sins, repent from sinning, and we are not only forgiven, but cleansed from unrighteousness.

Living a life pleasing to God from that moment, spending time reading His Word, allows us to draw close to God.

James 4:8       Draw nigh to God, and he will draw nigh to you. Cleanse your hands, ye sinners; and purify your hearts, ye double minded.
